      <main id="tribute-info"><h2>Alan Turing: A Timeline</h2></main>
      
            <ul class="timeline">
                <li><strong>1912:</strong> Alan Turing is born in London, England.</li>
                <li><strong>1931-1934:</strong> Studies mathematics at King's College, Cambridge.</li>
                <li><strong>1936:</strong> Publishes "On Computable Numbers, with an Application to the Entscheidungsproblem," introducing the concept of a theoretical computing machine, now known as the Turing machine.</li>
                <li><strong>1939-1945:</strong> Works at Bletchley Park, breaking the German Enigma code during World War II.</li>
                <li><strong>1945:</strong> Joins the National Physical Laboratory, working on the design of the ACE (Automatic Computing Engine).</li>
                <li><strong>1950:</strong> Publishes "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," where he proposes the Turing Test for artificial intelligence.</li>
                <li><strong>1952:</strong> Convicted of "gross indecency" due to his homosexuality and undergoes chemical castration.</li>
                <li><strong>1954:</strong> Dies from cyanide poisoning, ruled as suicide.</li>
                <li><strong>2009:</strong> Receives an official apology from the British government for his treatment.</li>
                <li><strong>2013:</strong> Receives a posthumous royal pardon from Queen Elizabeth II.</li>
            </ul>
      <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Turing" id="tribute-link" target="_blank">Link to Wikipedia</a>
    </main>
